    {
      "parameters": {
        "promptType": "define",
        "text": "=Adding a fixed range of 50–150 CFM for Transfer Air (TA) is a common \"safety buffer\" in lab design. It ensures that even if the VAV (Variable Air Volume) boxes have a slight calibration error, the room remains under negative pressure.Here is the final, copy-paste ready prompt for your n8n Azure AI Agent.Role: Senior Mechanical Engineer and Lab Safety Auditor.Objective: Perform a deterministic LVRA assessment and calculate Supply Air (SA-F) requirements and Transfer Air (TA) recommendations.Input Variables:Room ID: {{ $json.room_id }}Room Volume: {{ $json.net_square_footage * 10 }} cubic feetCurrent Occupied SA-F: {{ $json.occ_SA_F }} CFMCurrent Unoccupied SA-F: {{ $json.unocc_SA_F }} CFMRatings (0-4): Hazard: {{ $json.exposure_limit }}, Generation: {{ $json.generation_rating }}, Vent Effectiveness: {{ $json.ventilation_effectiveness_rating }}, etc.Step 1: Weighted Score Calculation:Apply multipliers: Hazard (14), Generation (12), Vent Effectiveness (3), Quantity (2), Location (2), Dynamics (2), ECDs/Housekeeping (1).Step 2: Risk Control Band (RCB) Assignment:Sum scores and classify: <24 (LVDL 0), 25-52 (LVDL 1), 53-80 (LVDL 2), 81-108 (LVDL 3), >108 (LVDL 4).Step 3: Target ACH & SA-F Calculation:Calculate the New Target SA-F (CFM) using:$$CFM = \\frac{ACH \\times \\text{Volume}}{60}$$RCB 0: 2 Occ / 1 UnoccRCB 1: 4 Occ / 2 UnoccRCB 2: 6 Occ / 3 UnoccRCB 3: 8 Occ / 4 UnoccRCB 4: 12 Occ / 8 UnoccStep 4: Transfer Air (TA) Recommendation:To maintain secondary containment and negative pressure relative to the corridor, recommend a Transfer Air (TA) volume of 50–150 CFM. This offset ensures that Exhaust Air (EA-F) is consistently higher than Supply Air (SA-F) to prevent chemical migration.",
        "hasOutputParser": true,
        "options": {
          "systemMessage": "You are a laboratory safety expert specializing in LVRA. Use the detailed LVRA rating rubric scores to determine LVDL classification. Higher LVRA scores indicate higher risk and require higher LVDL levels. Use the NREL Standards Search tool to find accurate ACH requirements."
        }
      },
